Plain — Examples
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


COMMENTS AND WHITESPACE

    ` Backtick starts a comment, ends at the line break.

    Whitespace and commas are interchangeable separators. These are the same:

        add 1, 2
        add 1 2


LITERALS

    ` Booleans
    yes
    no

    ` Nil
    none

    ` Integers
    42
    -7

    ` Reals
    3.14
    1.5e10

    ` Strings (single or double quotes, backslash escapes)
    "hello, world"
    'it\'s fine'


VARIABLES

    ` Assign with =
    x = 42;
    name = "Plain"

    ` Read a variable by using its name as an argument
    print x;
    print name


EXPRESSIONS

    ` Wrap any statement in [...] to use its result as a value
    print [add 1, 2];
    print [join "Hello, ", name, "!"];
    x = [multiply 6, 7]


ARITHMETIC

    ` Prefix form
    print [add 10, 3];         ` 13
    print [subtract 10, 3];    ` 7
    print [multiply 10, 3];    ` 30
    print [divide 10, 3];      ` 3
    print [modulo 10, 3]       ` 1

    ` Infix form — left side must be a named variable, not a literal
    x = 10;
    print [x + 3];             ` 13
    print [x - 3];             ` 7
    print [x * 3];             ` 30
    print [x / 3];             ` 3
    print [x % 3]              ` 1

    ` Reals promote automatically
    print [add 1, 0.5];        ` 1.5
    print [x + 0.5]            ` 10.5

    ` Infix is binary — chain via nesting for more than two operands
    print [add [x + 3] 2]      ` 15


COMPARISON

    x = 5;
    print [x = 5];               ` yes   (= means equality inside [...])
    print [x != 4];              ` yes
    print [x < 10];              ` yes
    print [x > 3];               ` yes
    print [x <= 5];              ` yes
    print [x >= 5]               ` yes

    ` The left operand must always be a named variable.
    ` To compare two literals, assign one to a variable first:
    `   a = "hello";
    `   print [a < "world"]    ` yes


LOGIC

    print [not yes]              ` no

    ` Prefix form — and/or accept multiple arguments
    print [and yes, yes];        ` yes
    print [or no, yes]           ` yes

    ` Infix and/or: left side must be a named variable
    a = yes;
    b = no;
    print [a and b];             ` no
    print [a or b]               ` yes

    ` Compound comparisons: nest expressions in prefix and/or
    x = 5;
    print [and [x > 0] [x < 10]];    ` yes
    print [or [x < 0] [x > 3]]       ` yes


STRINGS

    print [join "Hello, ", "world", "!"]    ` Hello, world!

    ` Numbers coerce to strings automatically
    print [join "Result: ", [add 1, 2]]     ` Result: 3


BLOCKS

    ` Curly braces create a deferred block — not evaluated until needed
    { print "I run when called" }

    ` Colon shorthand: opens a block, semicolon closes it
    : print "same thing" ;


IF

    x = 10;

    if [x > 5] {
        print "big"
    }

    ` With else — the second block is the else branch
    if [x > 5] {
        print "positive"
    } {
        print "not positive"
    }

    ` Colon shorthand (no else)
    if [x = 10]: print "exactly ten" ;


REPEAT

    ` Infinite loop — use break to exit
    x = 0;
    repeat {
        x = [x + 1];
        if [x = 3]: break ;
    };
    print x    ` 3

    ` Counted loop
    repeat 5 {
        print "hello"
    }

    ` Conditional loop — condition block is re-evaluated each iteration
    i = 0;
    repeat { i < 5 } {
        print i;
        i = [i + 1]
    }


BREAK

    ` Break exits the nearest repeat
    i = 0;
    repeat {
        if [i = 3]: break ;
        print i;
        i = [i + 1]
    }
    ` Prints: 0, 1, 2


FUNCTIONS (immutable)

    ` Named form
    function square {n} {
        return [n * n]
    };

    print [square 5]    ` 25

    ` Expression form — [function {parameters} {body}] returns a callable value
    double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }];
    print [double 5]    ` 10

    ` Functions cannot be reassigned after definition (immutable binding)


PROCEDURES (mutable)

    ` Named form
    procedure greet {name} {
        print [join "Hello, ", name, "!"]
    };

    greet "world"    ` Hello, world!

    ` Expression form — [procedure ...] returns a mutable, reassignable callable
    greet = [procedure {name} { print [join "Hey, ", name, "."] }];
    greet "Plain"    ` Hey, Plain.


RETURN

    function clamp {value, minimum, maximum} {
        if [value < minimum]: return minimum ;
        if [value > maximum]: return maximum ;
        return value
    };

    print [clamp 5, 0, 10];      ` 5
    print [clamp -3, 0, 10];     ` 0
    print [clamp 99, 0, 10]      ` 10


NESTED EXPRESSIONS

    function square {n} { return [n * n] };

    ` Nest expressions freely
    print [add [square 3] [square 4]]    ` 25

    ` Fibonacci
    function fibonacci {n} {
        if [n < 2]: return n ;
        return [add [fibonacci [n - 1]] [fibonacci [n - 2]]]
    };

    print [fibonacci 10]    ` 55


MULTIPLE STATEMENTS

    ` Semicolons separate statements on one line
    a = 1; b = 2; print [add a, b]    ` 3


FIRST-CLASS CALLABLES

    ` Built-in procedures are regular mutable bindings — store them, pass
    ` them as arguments, and invoke them exactly like user-defined callables.

    ` Store a built-in procedure in a variable
    branch = if;
    branch yes { print "yes" } { print "no" }    ` yes

    ` Pass a callable as an argument
    function apply {operation, a, b} {
        return [operation a, b]
    };

    print [apply add, 3, 4];         ` 7
    print [apply multiply, 3, 4];    ` 12

    ` Named comparison procedures — equal, less, greater — exist specifically
    ` for passing as first-class callables, since infix requires a named
    ` variable on the left and cannot be used in argument position directly.
    print [apply equal, 5, 5];       ` yes
    print [apply less, 3, 4];        ` yes
    print [apply greater, 4, 3]      ` yes

    ` Works with user-defined callables too
    function twice {f, x} {
        return [f [f x]]
    };

    double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }];
    print [twice double, 3]    ` 12  (3 * 2 * 2)

    ` Override a built-in procedure — no keywords are reserved
    ` Use [procedure ...] so the override remains reassignable
    add = [procedure {a, b} { result = [a + 1]; return [result + b] }];
    print [add 2, 3];    ` 6

    add = [procedure {a, b} { return [a + b] }];
    print [add 2, 3]     ` 5


OPERATOR OVERRIDES

    ` Operators (+, -, *, /, %, <, >, <=, >=, !=, and, or) can be
    ` overridden just like any other procedure. A single override covers
    ` both infix [a + b] and prefix [+ a b] call sites.

    ` Named procedure form — operator as name
    procedure + {a, b} {
        return [multiply a b]
    };

    x = 10;
    print [x + 3];    ` 30  (infix)
    print [+ x 3]     ` 30  (prefix — same callable)

    ` Expression form — equivalent result
    + = [procedure {a, b} { return [multiply a b] }]

    ` Override comparison operators the same way
    procedure < {a, b} {
        return [greater a, b]    ` deliberately reversed
    };

    x = 3;
    print [x < 10]    ` no  (reversed: 3 is not greater than 10)

    ` Restore a default operator by redefining it
    + = [procedure {a, b} { return [add a b] }]


KNOWN LIMITATIONS

    ` Infix requires the left operand to be a named variable.
    ` To compare a literal on the left, assign it to a variable first:
    `   a = "hello";
    `   print [a < "world"]    ` yes
    ` Or use equal/less/greater as first-class callables (see FIRST-CLASS CALLABLES).

    ` Infix is strictly binary. [a + b + c] only computes a + b.
    ` Chain arithmetic via nesting:
    `   [add [a + b] c]

    ` Compound conditions with infix and/or do not work as expected.
    ` [x > 0 and x < 10] only evaluates x > 0. Use prefix form:
    `   [and [x > 0] [x < 10]]

    ` There is no else keyword. The second block after if is the else branch:
    `   if condition { then } { else }

    ` function/procedure name {params} {body} only works when the name is
    ` not already bound as a non-operator variable. For rebinding a normal
    ` name, use the expression form:
    `   name = [procedure {params} {body}]
    ` Operator symbol names (+, -, etc.) are always safe to use in the
    ` named form regardless of whether they have been overridden before.
